Unsupervised Clustering - Case¶

Problem¶

ScooterX is a manufacturer of scooters. They regular collect user ratings on the usability, safety, and affordability of their scooters. Additionally, they collect a general rating from users and the collect the heights of users. They would like to understand how to segment out their customers and have provided you their rating data to work with. Currently, there are no classifications present.

In this case, we will learn how to apply K-means clustering and hiearchical clustering to identify classes.

Step 10: Hiearchical Clustering (Comparison)¶

Let's try hierarchical clustering as comparison. Recall that hierarchical clustering does not require us to define K clusters. However, note that the time-complexity of hierarchical clustering is $O(n^2)$ whereas K-means is $O(n)$, so it is more inefficient and is not always suitable for very large datasets. Fortunately, this dataset isn't too big!

The plot_dendogram function was taken from sklearn documentation.

In [194]:
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram

def plot_dendrogram(model, **kwargs): # **kwargs refers to keyword arguments
    # Create linkage matrix and then plot the dendrogram

    # create the counts of samples under each node
    counts = np.zeros(model.children_.shape[0]) # the children refer to the branches of the model
    n_samples = len(model.labels_) # this how many samples there
    for i, merge in enumerate(model.children_):
        current_count = 0
        for child_idx in merge:
            if child_idx < n_samples:
                current_count += 1  # leaf node
            else:
                current_count += counts[child_idx - n_samples]
        counts[i] = current_count

    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([model.children_, model.distances_,
                                      counts]).astype(float) # stack chidren, distances, and counts

    # Plot the corresponding dendrogram
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)

# setting distance_threshold=0 ensures we compute the full tree.
model = AgglomerativeClustering(distance_threshold=0, n_clusters=None)

model = model.fit(X)
plt.figure(figsize=(25,10))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
# plot the top three levels of the dendrogram
plot_dendrogram(model, truncate_mode='level', p=3)
plt.xlabel("Number of points in node (or index of point if no parenthesis).")
plt.ylabel("Distance")
plt.axhline(y=7.1, c='k')
plt.show()

Step 11: Split into Clusters¶

We can make any set of clustering based on how we cut the tree. Example below.

In [195]:
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram

def plot_dendrogram(model, **kwargs):
    # Create linkage matrix and then plot the dendrogram
    
    # create the counts of samples under each node
    counts = np.zeros(model.children_.shape[0]) # model.children_ refers to the child nodes
    n_samples = len(model.labels_) # we want to count the number of child nodes in each branch
    for i, merge in enumerate(model.children_): 
        current_count = 0
        for child_idx in merge:
            if child_idx < n_samples:
                current_count += 1  # leaf node
            else:
                current_count += counts[child_idx - n_samples]
        counts[i] = current_count

    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([model.children_, model.distances_,
                                      counts]).astype(float) # stack up the child nodes, the distances between the ndoes, and the node counts

    # Plot the corresponding dendrogram
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)

# setting distance_threshold=0 ensures we compute the full tree.
model = AgglomerativeClustering(distance_threshold=0, n_clusters=None)

model = model.fit(X)
plt.figure(figsize=(25,10))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
# plot the top three levels of the dendrogram
plot_dendrogram(model, truncate_mode='level', p=3)
plt.xlabel("Number of points in node (or index of point if no parenthesis).")
plt.ylabel("Distance")
plt.axhline(y=7.1, c='k')
plt.show()

K-Means Clustering¶

In [201]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline
df = pd.read_csv("data/ratings.csv", index_col = 0)
X = df.iloc[:, [0,1,2,3]].values
kmeans3 = KMeans(n_clusters=3)
y_kmeans3 = kmeans3.fit_predict(X)
df['Class'] = np.array(y_kmeans3)
sns.pairplot(df, hue = "Class")

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [202]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram
%matplotlib inline

df = pd.read_csv("data/ratings.csv", index_col = 0)
X = df.iloc[:, [0,1,2,3]].values

def plot_dendrogram(model, **kwargs):
    # Create linkage matrix and then plot the dendrogram
    
    # create the counts of samples under each node
    counts = np.zeros(model.children_.shape[0]) # model.children_ refers to the child nodes
    n_samples = len(model.labels_) # we want to count the number of child nodes in each branch
    for i, merge in enumerate(model.children_): 
        current_count = 0
        for child_idx in merge:
            if child_idx < n_samples:
                current_count += 1  # leaf node
            else:
                current_count += counts[child_idx - n_samples]
        counts[i] = current_count

    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([model.children_, model.distances_,
                                      counts]).astype(float) # stack up the child nodes, the distances between the ndoes, and the node counts

    # Plot the corresponding dendrogram
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)

# setting distance_threshold=0 ensures we compute the full tree.
model = AgglomerativeClustering(distance_threshold=0, n_clusters=None)

model = model.fit(X)
plt.figure(figsize=(25,10))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
# plot the top three levels of the dendrogram
plot_dendrogram(model, truncate_mode='level', p=3)
plt.xlabel("Number of points in node (or index of point if no parenthesis).")
plt.ylabel("Distance")
#plt.axhline(y=7.1, c='k') 
plt.show()

The above can be cut in any way to make all possible clusterings.

Conclusion¶

From a set of just features, we were able to generate clusters in an unsupervised way. Now, the client has interpretable data that can be used to segment out customers!
